               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-172-person917">
                  CAROLINE 
                  GLADDING
               <interp inst="t18250915-172-person917" type="surname" value="GLADDING"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-172-person917" type="given" value="CAROLINE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-172-person917" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Samuel Gladding. On the 30th of July, between twelve and one o'clock, I was up stairs, and was called down by my child. I missed my shawl off a line in the yard, where it had hung to dry; I went to Sowerby's, the pawnbroker's, and found the shawl and prisoner there.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-172-person918">
                  JOHN 
                  TUSHAW
               <interp inst="t18250915-172-person918" type="surname" value="TUSHAW"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-172-person918" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-172-person918" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a weaver. I saw the prisoner go through Mr. Gladding's pailing, and in a few minutes he came out with a bundle under his arm - I saw the corner of a white shawl.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-172-person919">
